From the theory of SIMILAR to a runnable simulation

	The SIMILAR API suite was designed to provide a direct bijection between the theoretical concepts developed in SIMILAR and their implementation. This bijection facilitates the comprehension of the code and embodies the proof that the benefits of the SIMILAR meta-model are not purely theoretical.
	
* Bijection between theory and code
	
	The following array describes the correspondence between the theoretical concepts of SIMILAR and their implementation. Note that this list is not exhaustive and focuses
	on the core concepts of SIMILAR. See the documentation of the various classes of the micro-kernel to have a better insight on the correspondance between the theory and this
	implementation.
	
** Level-related elements:
	
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| <<Full name in SIMILAR>>                     | <<Element in the SIMILAR API suite>>                                                  |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Level                                        | Instances of the <<<ILevel>>> interface. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Perception relation graph of the simulation  | Spread among the instances of the <<<ILevel>>> interface of the simulation.           |
|                                              | The out neighborhood of the perception relation graph is returned by a call to the    |
|                                              | <"getPerceptibleLevels()"> method of the <<<ILevel>>> interface.                      |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Influence relation graph of the simulation   | Spread among the instances of the <<<ILevel>>> interface of the simulation.           |
|                                              | The out neighborhood of the influence relation graph is returned by a call to the     |
|                                              | <"getInfluenceableLevels()"> method of the <<<ILevel>>> interface.                    |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Public local dynamic state of the simulation | Instances of the <<<IDynamicStateMap>>> interface. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Public local dynamic state of a level        | Instances of the <<<IPublicLocalDynamicState>>> interface. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Consistent dynamic state of a level          | Instances of the <<<ConsistentPublicLocalDynamicState>>> class. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Transitory dynamic state of a level          | Instances of the <<<TransitoryPublicLocalDynamicState>>> class. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Reaction process of a level                  | <"makeRegularReaction(...)"> and <"makeSystemReaction(...)"> methods of the |
|                                              | <<<ILevel>>> interface. |
*----------------------------------------------+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
<<Link between the theory of SIMILAR and Classes/Interfaces or other software elements of the micro-kernel (levels)>>

